Project Overview
This project applies Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to the well-known Breast Cancer Wisconsin Dataset (built into scikit-learn). The dataset contains 569 patient records, each described by 30 numerical features computed from digitized images of fine needle aspirate (FNA) of breast masses.
The goal of this project is to:

Understand the structure and correlation among 30 medical features
Use PCA to reduce dimensionality from 30 → 2 components
Visualize whether the reduced data can still clearly distinguish between Malignant and Benign tumors
Interpret which features drive each principal component


The Core Problem
Medical datasets often contain dozens of highly correlated features. For example, radius_mean, perimeter_mean, and area_mean all measure similar aspects of a tumor cell — they carry overlapping information. This leads to:

Redundant features that add noise, not signal
Difficulty visualizing high-dimensional data
Slower, overfitting-prone machine learning models

PCA solves this by finding new axes (principal components) that capture the maximum variance in the data — effectively compressing the information without losing what matters.

💡 Key Results
MetricValueOriginal Features30Components after PCA2 (for visualization)Variance Retained~63% with 2 PCsComponents for 90% Variance7 PCs (out of 30)Components for 95% Variance10 PCs (out of 30)Classes Visually Separable?✅ Yes — clearly in 2D
📉 Dimensionality Reduction Impact
Before PCA:   30 features ████████████████████████████████
After PCA:     2 features ██                                  (for visualization)
              7 features ███████                             (retains 90% info)
             10 features ██████████                          (retains 95% info)

With just 7 out of 30 features, we can retain 90% of all the information in the dataset. That's a 76% reduction in complexity.


📊 Visualizations Included
1. Class Distribution
Shows the balance between Malignant (212) and Benign (357) cases in the dataset.
2. Correlation Heatmap
Reveals that many of the 30 features are highly correlated (r > 0.8) with each other — this is exactly the condition where PCA delivers the most value.
3. Scree Plot
Displays the variance explained by each individual principal component, helping identify the "elbow point."
4. Cumulative Variance Plot
Shows how many components are needed to retain 80%, 90%, and 95% of the total variance.
5. PCA 2D Scatter Plot ⭐
The most impactful visual — plots all 569 patients in 2D space (PC1 vs PC2), colored by diagnosis. Despite compressing 30 features into 2, Malignant and Benign cases form clearly separated clusters.
6. Feature Loadings Heatmap
Shows the contribution of each original feature to PC1 and PC2, revealing which medical measurements are most important.


